```suggestion
lemma rdrop_add {l : List α} (i j : ℕ) :
```

The type `α` already is available as a variable. In fact `l` is also available, but as explicit argument. So adding it manually to make it implicit is fine.

```suggestion
lemma rdrop_append_length {l₁ l₂ : List α} :
```

```suggestion
lemma rdrop_append {l₁ l₂ : List α} (i : ℕ) :
```
Is there a reason for LHS/RHS inconsistency between `List.drop_drop` and `List.rdrop_add`?
I didn't see one - flipped.

```suggestion
```
`rdrop_append_length_add`? Also, could you please add lemma `rdrop_append_of_le_length` saying `k ≤ length l₂ → List.rdrop (l₁ ++ l₂) k = l₁ ++ List.rdrop l₂ k`?
Added; my proof can certainly be golfed further.
This is a drive-by clean-up: my understanding is this is worthwhile anyway. It also makes the next lines nicer to write, as I can re-use `l`.
